The Good Witch's Charm is the fifth "Good Witch" movie, not to be confused with the TV series that just concluded its second season.  Cassie is now mayor or Middleton and taking care of her new baby.  She is charming, mysterious and possibly magical.  Catherine Bell's character is delightful  This franchise follows the Hallmark formula to a T, which can be a good thing or bad thing according to your viewpoint.  This gentle series promotes peace, love and understanding through Cassie's zen-like advice to others.  She seems to take her own advice to heart, as well, making her a very likeable character indeed.  (Why couldn't my mother have been more like Cassie?)  I can almost hear David Carradine's peace-loving Shaolin monk character from the 70's TV series Kung Fu in Cassie's pronouncements.  So if you are looking for a cultural and spiritual palate cleanser from all the ugliness the world has to offer, this might just be your raspberry sorbet of the soul.

It's innocent, and okay for family viewing.  Don't expect Shakespeare, but the actors are competent, and manage to successfully carry the often predictable plots with their charming personalities.  Good for an evening when you just want something relaxing, not challenging, or if you are watching with children.  Doubt if it would hold a very young child's interest, but would certainly not frighten them, or present something untoward for their development.  I am not strictly religious, but even if I was, I saw nothing harmful or derogatory to anyone's belief system, just some sweet fairy tale aspects, though not always well developed enough for my taste.  Really more a three and a half star film.

This is my pick for our shortlist of Christmas Holiday *watch with little kids after a big dinner when you don't really need to see stuff explode or pole dancing as a backdrop" movies.  A small town with growing pains wondering how to manage a needed boost in tourism has a witch for a mayor, a greedy merchant in Margaret Thatcher drag, and a sensationalist reporter, all politely duking it out.

Bad Teenagers, too. This film's sort of typical Hallmark Hall studio: thoughtfully produced and candy coated, stuff that makes me nod out. But if you're looking for a sweet family film to nod out on that won't offend anyone except maybe uber-grinches, GOOD WITCH's CHARM is possibly a notch better than many Hallmark Hall films. Refreshing change from typical let's build the snow man or rescue the silly dog fare. Warning: there is some cookie baking going on in this film.

Ms. Bell continues to entertain with her "Good Witch" movies.  These movies can be watched together as a family or by the younger set alone without parental fear of them being exposed to the "F" word, bare T&A, humping or even inferred humping or in my opinion, the disgusting interracial pawing (or worse) exhibited in so many of todays shows.  Hallmark has announced that Ms Bell will be starring in a made for T.V. series of The Good Witch premiering sometime early 2015.  It appears most of the same cast members will remain the same as in the movie presentations.  Still miss her and Harm tho.  Their on-screen chemistry was much better than hers and her current on-screen significant others.
